<subSubSection id="5AEA65651624FFE9FB02FBFCF7FBF65A" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" type="description">
<paragraph id="124F36EE1624FFE9FB02FBFCF797F8B9" blockId="25.[1273,2257,1123,2541]" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">
This group comprises the two taxa treated by 
<bibRefCitation id="76614B1F1624FFE9F7CBFBFCFAA0FB0F" author="Crosskey, R. W." pageId="25" pageNumber="110" pagination="33 - 140" refId="ref24684" refString="Crosskey, R. W., 1965. A systematic revision of the Ameniinae (Diptera: Calliphoridae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Entomology 16: 33 - 140." type="journal article" year="1965">Crosskey (1965)</bibRefCitation>
as subspecies of 
<emphasis id="2084EAFC1624FFE9F96EFB0EF7F7FB0F" box="[1686,2096,1169,1208]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">
<taxonomicName id="D5F04D6D1624FFE9F96EFB0EF88EFB0F" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[1686,1865,1169,1208]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Amenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonina">A. leonina</taxonomicName>
: A. l. 
<taxonomicName id="D5F04D6D1624FFE9F84DFB0EF7F7FB0F" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[1973,2096,1169,1208]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Amenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonina">leonina</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="2084EAFC1624FFE9F77EFB0EFA20FB51" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">
A. 1. 
<taxonomicName id="D5F04D6D1624FFE9FB02FB5FFA25FB51" authorityName="Colless" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName=", Crosskey" baseAuthorityYear="1965" box="[1274,1506,1216,1254]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Amenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albomaculata">albomaculata</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
As discussed in Part 1, the two are to a large extent allopatric, but with some significant occurrences of each within the range of the other. Males are morphometrically distinct on the basis of relative head width, which correlates with the other characters used in the key above, but in southeastern 
<collectingRegion id="D034F80C1624FFE9F887FA3AF789FA7B" box="[1919,2126,1445,1484]" country="Australia" name="Queensland" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">Queensland</collectingRegion>
, in the general vicinity ofBrisbane, intermediate specimens occur, suggesting some degree of introgression of genotypes. However, this could be the result of ecological disturbance, and specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="D5F04D6D1624FFE9F9D0F9C2F8FAF933" authorityName="Colless" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName=", Crosskey" baseAuthorityYear="1965" box="[1576,1853,1629,1668]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Amenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albomaculata">
<emphasis id="2084EAFC1624FFE9F9D0F9C2F8FAF933" box="[1576,1853,1629,1668]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">A. albomaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Mackay and of 
<taxonomicName id="D5F04D6D1624FFE9F753F9C2FABCF905" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1775" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Amenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonina">
<emphasis id="2084EAFC1624FFE9F753F9C2FABCF905" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">A. leonina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Sydney, suggest that introgression is not general. For that reason, specific status seems to me most suitable, and I am restoring the taxa on that basis.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="124F36EE1624FFE9FAD1F88AF9FEF6BF" blockId="25.[1273,2257,1123,2541]" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">
Members of the group can be identified by the characters given in the key. They can be recognised with the naked eye by the large size, the metallic blue or greenish-blue body colour, the conspicuous pair of prescutal dorsocentral pale stripes, and the pale lateral spots of abdominal T3 not extending on to the dorsum. The rather similar 
<taxonomicName id="D5F04D6D1624FFE9F750F864FA7BF7E7" baseAuthorityName="Malloch" baseAuthorityYear="1930" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Amenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicornis">
<emphasis id="2084EAFC1624FFE9F750F864FA7BF7E7" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">A. longicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is usually smaller, purplish-black in colour, and the lateral pale spots on T3 clearly extend on to the dorsum. As in the 
<taxonomicName id="D5F04D6D1624FFE9F9BFF71AF937F71C" box="[1607,1776,2181,2219]" class="Insecta" family="Calliphoridae" genus="Amenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imperialis">
<emphasis id="2084EAFC1624FFE9F9BFF71AF937F71C" box="[1607,1776,2181,2219]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">imperialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, the male terminalia show no attributes useful for identifying the group or its individual species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="124F36EE1624FFE9FAD1F690F7FBF65A" blockId="25.[1273,2257,1123,2541]" pageId="25" pageNumber="110">
<bibRefCitation id="76614B1F1624FFE9FAD1F690F994F682" author="Crosskey, R. W." box="[1321,1619,2319,2357]" pageId="25" pageNumber="110" pagination="33 - 140" refId="ref24684" refString="Crosskey, R. W., 1965. A systematic revision of the Ameniinae (Diptera: Calliphoridae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Entomology 16: 33 - 140." type="journal article" year="1965">Crosskey's (1965)</bibRefCitation>
detailed descriptions hold fairly well, and I deal below mainly with additional differences that have appeared in the more abundant material now available. The curious geographic distributions displayed in this group are discussed in Part 3 (Zoogeography and Evolution).
</paragraph>
